## Incorrect Patterns

### ❌ BAD: Unnecessary Data Transformation

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG: Creating wrapper objects
export default async function ProjectsPage() {
  const { data } = await listProjects(dc, { limit: 20 });
  
  // ❌ BAD: Unnecessary transformation
  const transformedProjects = data.projects.map((project) => ({
    id: project.id,
    title: project.name, // Renaming field
    currentStatus: project.status, // Renaming field
    created: project.createdAt, // Renaming field
    // ... other fields
  }));
  
  return <ProjectList projects={transformedProjects} />;
}
```

**Why this is wrong:**
- Creates unnecessary mapping code
- Loses type safety
- Makes it harder to track data flow
- Database schema changes require updates in multiple places

### ❌ BAD: Wrapper Objects

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG: Wrapping data in unnecessary objects
const wrappedData = {
  items: data.projects,
  count: data.projects.length,
  metadata: {
    fetchedAt: new Date().toISOString(),
  },
};

return <ProjectList data={wrappedData} />;
```

**Why this is wrong:**
- Adds unnecessary nesting
- Makes data access more complex
- Doesn't match database structure

### ❌ BAD: Changing Field Names

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG: Changing field names to match "frontend conventions"
const frontendProjects = data.projects.map((p) => ({
  projectId: p.id, // ❌ Changed from 'id'
  projectName: p.name, // ❌ Changed from 'name'
  projectStatus: p.status, // ❌ Changed from 'status'
}));
```

**Why this is wrong:**
- Database uses `id`, not `projectId`
- Creates confusion about data source
- Makes debugging harder
- Type safety is lost

### ❌ BAD: Adding Placeholder Data

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG: Adding fake/placeholder data
const projectsWithDefaults = data.projects.map((p) => ({
  ...p,
  name: p.name || 'Unknown Project', // ❌ Should be null/undefined
  status: p.status || 'pending', // ❌ Should be null/undefined
}));
```

**Why this is wrong:**
- Hides missing data issues
- Makes it unclear what data is real vs placeholder
- Missing data is normal — keep `null` / `undefined` and handle it at the
  render layer (see `key-conventions-rules.mdc` § "Do not invent placeholder
  data")

