## Type Safety Across Layers

### Using inferred types

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: Infer row types from Drizzle table objects
import { projects } from '@app/db/schema';
import type { InferSelectModel } from 'drizzle-orm';

type Project = InferSelectModel<typeof projects>;

export function ProjectCard({ project }: { project: Project }) {
  return <div>{project.name}</div>;
}
```

### Type Definitions Should Match Database

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: Type definition matches database schema
interface Project {
  id: string; // UUID in DB → string in TS
  name: string; // TEXT in DB → string in TS
  status: string; // TEXT in DB → string in TS
  createdAt: string; // TIMESTAMP in DB → ISO string in TS
  deletedAt: string | null; // TIMESTAMP in DB → ISO string | null in TS
}

// ❌ BAD: Type doesn't match database
interface Project {
  projectId: string; // ❌ DB uses 'id', not 'projectId'
  projectName: string; // ❌ DB uses 'name', not 'projectName'
}
```

---

## Migration Guidelines

### When Database Schema Changes

1. **Update SQL / migration** (source of truth)
2. **Update Drizzle schema** in `packages/db/src/schema/*`
3. **Run `pnpm -F @app/db generate` (or project migrate workflow)** so migrations stay ordered
4. **Update backend + frontend** to use the new column names as-is
5. **No transformation layer needed** — direct mapping

### Example: Adding a New Field

```sql
-- 1. Database: Add field
ALTER TABLE projects ADD COLUMN description TEXT;
```

```typescript
// 2. Drizzle: add matching column on `projects` table object
// description: text('description'),
```

```typescript
// 3. Frontend: Use new field directly
export function ProjectCard({ project }: { project: Project }) {
  return (
    <div>
      <h3>{project.name}</h3>
      {project.description && <p>{project.description}</p>}
    </div>
  );
}
```

---

## Checklist

Before submitting code, verify:

- [ ] Data structure matches database schema
- [ ] No unnecessary field renaming
- [ ] No wrapper objects created
- [ ] Types are generated from schema (or match exactly)
- [ ] Transformations only for display (date formatting, etc.)
- [ ] No placeholder/fake data added
- [ ] Direct data passing from query → component
- [ ] TypeScript types match database schema

---

## Common Mistakes

### ❌ Mistake 1: Renaming Fields

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG
const frontendData = dbData.map((item) => ({
  itemId: item.id, // Don't rename!
  itemName: item.name, // Don't rename!
}));
```

### ❌ Mistake 2: Creating Wrapper Objects

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG
const wrapped = {
  data: projects,
  meta: { count: projects.length },
};
```

### ❌ Mistake 3: Unnecessary Mapping

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG
const mapped = projects.map((p) => ({
  id: p.id,
  name: p.name,
  // ... mapping all fields unnecessarily
}));
```

### ❌ Mistake 4: Changing Data Structure

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG: Flattening nested structure
const flattened = {
  projectId: project.id,
  productName: project.product.name, // Should keep nested
};
```

---

## Summary

**Key Principles:**

1. **Database schema is authoritative** - All layers must align
2. **Minimize transformations** - Only for display formatting
3. **Preserve structure** - Pass data directly through layers
4. **Use generated types** - Ensure type safety
5. **No renaming** - Keep field names consistent
6. **No wrappers** - Avoid unnecessary object nesting
7. **Direct mapping** - Map database → backend → frontend directly

**Remember:** If you find yourself transforming data "to match frontend conventions," you're probably doing it wrong. The frontend should adapt to the database structure, not the other way around.
